        "user": "How does \"prismatic affinity\" differ from perspectivism / perspective-dependence?",
        "assistant": "Working from your definition, the difference here is subtler than the ambiguity contrast — but it's a real one, and it turns on **what varies** and **why**.\n\n## Perspective-Dependence\n- Variation is driven by the **observer's position, standpoint, or situation** — spatial, temporal, cultural, epistemic\n- Different descriptions are typically **reconcilable in principle**: they're partial views of a shared underlying object, and one could (at least conceptually) triangulate among them\n- The observer is largely **passive** with respect to framing — you see what your standpoint affords\n- Classic example: the blind men and the elephant. Each touches a different part; the descriptions differ because of *where they stand*, and a god's-eye view would unify them.\n\n## Prismatic Affinity\n- Variation is driven by the **angle of attention or framing** the observer brings — an active stance, not just a location\n- Different descriptions are **non-overlapping** and not straightforwardly reconcilable; there is no neutral synthesis that absorbs them without remainder\n- The observer **constitutes** the framing through how they attend, not merely through where they are\n- The object's apparent identity *shifts coherently with* the framing — it isn't that each framing reveals a piece of one identity; each framing produces a complete identity of its own\n\n## The Core Contrast\n\n| Feature | Perspective-Dependence | Prismatic Affinity |\n|---|---|---|\n| Source of variation | Observer's position/standpoint | Observer's framing/attention |\n| Underlying object | One object, partially seen | One object, multiply identified |\n| Reconcilability | Views can be aggregated | Views resist aggregation |\n| Observer's role | Situated | Constitutive (via framing) |\n| Completeness per view | Partial | Complete |\n\n## Putting It Compactly\n\n- **Perspective-dependence**: *I see a different side of the same thing because I'm standing somewhere.*\n- **Prismatic affinity**: *I see a different thing entirely because I'm attending in a certain way — and so do you, just as completely, attending differently.*\n\n## An Illustration\n\nConsider a poem.\n- *Perspective-dependent* reading: a reader from one cultural background notices certain allusions; another notices different ones. In principle, a sufficiently informed reader could integrate both.\n- *Prismatically affine* reading: read as a love poem, it is fully and coherently a love poem; read as a political allegory, it is fully and coherently that. Neither reading is partial, and no master-reading subsumes both without flattening each.\n\nPerspective-dependence preserves a single object behind the views. Prismatic affinity, as you've defined it, lets the object's identity itself bend with the framing — without collapsing into ambiguity, because each bent identity is internally whole.\n\nWant to test it against a harder case — say, scientific models of the same phenomenon (wave/particle), or competing historical narratives? Those sit interestingly on the boundary.",
