        "user": "How does \"prismatic affinity\" differ from polysemy?",
        "assistant": "Good question — polysemy is probably the closest neighbor we've considered so far, and the contrast requires more care than the previous two.\n\n## Polysemy\n- A property of **signs, words, or symbols** — a single lexical item carries multiple **related** meanings\n- The multiplicity is **stored in the sign itself**: \"bank\" (financial institution / riverside / tilt of an aircraft) has its senses listed, conventionalized, and learnable\n- Context **selects** which sense is active; the others recede but remain available in the lexicon\n- The senses are typically **enumerable** and historically traceable (often via metaphorical or metonymic extension from a core sense)\n- Located in **language and convention**\n\n## Prismatic Affinity\n- A property of the **perceived object** itself, not of a sign that refers to it\n- The multiplicity is **generated at the moment of attention**, not stored in advance\n- Framing **constitutes** the identity rather than selecting from a menu of pre-given ones\n- The coherent identities are not necessarily enumerable — new framings can yield new internally consistent identities\n- Located in **the encounter between observer and object**, not in convention\n\n## The Core Contrast\n\n| Feature | Polysemy | Prismatic Affinity |\n|---|---|---|\n| Locus | The sign/word | The object as attended to |\n| Source of multiplicity | Conventional, lexicalized | Framing-generated |\n| Mode of selection | Context picks a stored sense | Attention produces an identity |\n| Enumerability | Typically finite, listable | Open-ended |\n| Relation among readings | Historically/semantically related | Need not be related at all |\n\n## Putting It Compactly\n\n- **Polysemy**: *one word carries several settled senses; context picks one.*\n- **Prismatic affinity**: *one object yields several coherent identities; attention enacts one.*\n\n## An Illustration\n\nTake the word \"light.\"\n- *Polysemy*: it means electromagnetic radiation, or low weight, or not serious — three conventionalized senses, learnable from a dictionary, selected by context.\n- *Prismatic affinity* (of, say, a candle flame): attended to as a physical phenomenon, it is fully a combustion event; attended to devotionally, it is fully a votive presence; attended to aesthetically, it is fully a moving form. None of these is a \"sense\" stored in the candle; each is constituted in the attending.\n\n## A Subtler Boundary\n\nPolysemy and prismatic affinity can look alike when an object is **culturally encoded** with multiple framings (a flag, a cross, a national anthem). One could argue these have something like lexicalized framings — quasi-polysemous identities. The distinguishing test, on your definition, would be:\n\n- If the multiplicity is **inherited from convention** and **selected by context**, it leans polysemous.\n- If the multiplicity is **produced by the angle of attention** and the framings are **not pre-stored** but enacted, it leans prismatic.\n\nPolysemy is something a sign *has*. Prismatic affinity, as you've defined it, is something an object *does* under attention.\n\nWant to push into the hardest neighbor next — **aspect perception** (Wittgenstein's seeing-as)? That one shares the \"framing constitutes identity\" feature and may be the toughest to distinguish cleanly.",
