        "assistant": "# Prismatic Affinity\n\nA **prismatic affinity** is a concept from geometry, specifically within the field of affine transformations. The term comes from the Greek word \"prisma,\" referring to something that is split or separated.\n\n## Definition\n\nA prismatic affinity (also called an **axial affinity** or **shear-like affinity**) is a special type of affine transformation in a plane or space that has the following key properties:\n\n1. **It has a fixed line (or plane)** called the **axis of the affinity** — every point on this line/plane remains unchanged by the transformation.\n\n2. **Points not on the axis are mapped along parallel lines** in a specific direction.\n\n3. **The ratio of distances** from corresponding points to the axis (measured in the direction of displacement) is constant. This ratio is called the **coefficient** or **ratio of the affinity**.\n\n## In the Plane (2D)\n\nA prismatic affinity in 2D maps each point P to a point P' such that:\n- The line PP' is parallel to a fixed direction\n- The midpoint behavior preserves the ratio: if P projects onto the axis at point M, then **MP'/MP = k** (a constant)\n\nWhen the displacement direction is **perpendicular** to the axis, it's called an **orthogonal affinity**. When it's at another angle, it's an **oblique affinity**.\n\n## Common Examples\n\n- **Shears** (when k = 1 with displacement parallel to axis... wait, this would be a shear)\n- **Stretching/compression** along one direction (orthogonal affinity)\n- The transformation that maps a circle to an ellipse is a classic orthogonal affinity\n\n## Applications\n\nPrismatic affinities are useful in:\n- **Descriptive geometry** for constructing conic sections\n- **Computer graphics** for certain deformations\n- **Engineering drawings** for projections\n- Proving geometric properties by mapping simpler shapes (like circles) to more complex ones (like ellipses)\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any particular aspect, such as the mathematical formulation or specific applications?",
